id":"5"}},"exam":{"data":null}}},{"type":"questions","id":"206","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/206"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.26,0.14,0.29,0.2,0.12]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"206"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"53992"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"206","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/206"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"206"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"39463"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1984"},{"type":"tags","id":"2069"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"14572"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14573"},{"type":"contributions","id":"16241"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42029"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44022"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"53992","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/53992"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 12-year-old boy presents to the Emergency Department with his parent three hours after sustaining a dog bite to his left leg. He has no significant medical history and his tetanus immunisation is up to date. Several years ago, he developed a rash after taking amoxicillin for a chest infection. He does not take any regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well. His pulse rate is 90/min, blood pressure 110/60 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 99% on room air, and temperature 37.2\u00b0C. There are two small shallow gashes on the skin of his left leg, with no surrounding erythema or oozing from the wounds. His left leg is neurovascularly intact, with preserved range of motion.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate management plan in addition to cleaning and dressing the wounds?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Oral clindamycin","Oral amoxicillin and clavulanic acid","No additional specific treatment","Oral trimethoprim-sulfamethoxazole and clindamycin","Oral trimethoprim-sulfamethoxazole"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EIn this case, \u003Cstrong\u003Eno additional specific treatment\u003C/strong\u003E beyond wound cleaning and dressing is necessary. The patient presents with a superficial dog bite that occurred only three hours ago. He is otherwise healthy, and the wound shows no signs of infection such as erythema or purulent discharge. These factors indicate a low risk of infection, and therefore, prophylactic antibiotics are not routinely recommended.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOral clindamycin\u003C/strong\u003E is not necessary in this case. While it can be used as an alternative in patients with penicillin allergy when antibiotics are indicated, this patient does not require antibiotic prophylaxis based on the nature and timing of the injury.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOral amoxicillin and clavulanic acid\u003C/strong\u003E is a common choice for antibiotic prophylaxis in animal bites when indicated. However, in this case, it\u0027s not necessary due to the low risk of infection. Additionally, the patient has a history of developing a rash with amoxicillin, which would make this option less suitable even if antibiotics were needed.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe combination of \u003Cstrong\u003Eoral trimethoprim-sulfamethoxazole and clindamycin\u003C/strong\u003E is an excessive treatment for this case. This combination might be considered in severe cases or when broader coverage is needed, but it\u0027s not appropriate for a simple, low-risk dog bite.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOral trimethoprim-sulfamethoxazole\u003C/strong\u003E alone is not typically a first-line choice for dog bites. When antibiotics are indicated, broader coverage including anaerobic bacteria is usually preferred.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAccording to guidelines, antibiotic prophylaxis for animal bites is recommended in high-risk situations such as puncture wounds, cat bites, bites to the hand or face, delayed presentation (\u003E8 hours), immunocompromised patients, or when there\u0027s evidence of infection. None of these factors are present in this case. The key to management is thorough wound cleaning, appropriate dressing, and patient education about signs of infection to watch for. Tetanus prophylaxis should be considered, but this patient is up to date with his immunisations.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Not all animal bites require antibiotic treatment.","Superficial dog bites in healthy individuals can often be managed with local wound care alone.","Antibiotic prophylaxis is indicated for high-risk animal bites, including puncture wounds, cat bites, and bites in immunocompromised patients."],"references":["Electronic Therapeutic Guidelines 2020, Principles of management of bites and clenched-fist injuries.","Hurt JB, Maday KR. Management and treatment of animal bites. JAAPA 2018; 31:27-31."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"39463"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"206"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"39463","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/39463"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-09-28T15:20:50+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-09-28T15:21:52+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"206"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"53992"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"